title: For Sale:  SMITH & WESSON ~ PRE-MODEL 27 3.5-Inch Shipped to QUANTICO in 1950...XLNT w/ Box.
postcontent: Here's a desirable Smith & Wesson revolver! This is a very early "Pre-Model 27" .357 Magnum. Even more interesting, it is fitted with the short 3.5-Inch barrel that was shipped to Quantico, Virginia, home of the FBI Academy! Built on the big-N frame with five screws, this revolver is factory finished in the highly polished bright blue. The "Pre-Model 27" was introduced in 1950 with the advent of the "short action" and this is a very early example! The Standard Catalog of Smith & Wesson mentions one source stating that the first Pre-Model 27 was serial number S75514, shipped 11/13/1950. This revolver is serial number S75969...but it shipped February 10, 1950!This revolver is in excellent overall condition.

title: For Sale:  REMINGTON RAND, ERRS, 1911A1
postcontent: WWII Remington Rand 1911A1, ERRS gun (Experimental Remington Rand Series), Serial Number 25,....According to Charles Clawson books the ERRS were created by Remington Rand for conducting experiments to improve their product. They were later presented to officials and employees of the company. There may have been only one batch of these pistols totaling less than 150 in number....This ERRS gun is 100% Original and Authentic. This one is in excellent condition, you can tell it was special to someone. I would say not hardly used or fired much. These ERRS guns being experimental in design there was not a standard specification for the parts and finish. Anything went and some even seem to have been made from odds and ends of parts. I have seen many of these guns and seems like small groups of them are similar and those groups greatly differ from the other groups. I would say the one seen the most is the Parkerized finish and some or all Parkerized small parts....like this one. Slide and Frame are exact same in color despite what the pics might show. Parkerized guns are a bit*h to photograph....None of the other ERRS guns had Govt acceptance proofs (like this one) or markings of any kind on the frame except the serial number and a "P" on the left front trigger guard....of which I have seen three with the P and found a picture of one with P on the internet that belonged to the Rem Rand chief inspector Peter D. Strolis, he had serial 45. I have several pics of up close serial numbers from other ERRS guns, other ERRS gun pics and a few websites with some info....if you are serious about buying I would be more then happy to send that stuff to you. On the note of Serial number pics I have....One thing I find interesting is the NO prefix at serial...the O on all the ERRS guns I've seen seems to be sized odd, different then standard production, It's almost looks like they used a Zero instead of letter O, and they are all like that. Here is one link from coolgunsite.com which is widely respected in 1911a1's....it mentions that Several of these pistols were found in a Remington Rand vault in Buffalo NY in the early 1960's. These ERRS and EXP pistols are highly prized by collectors..... http://www.coolgunsite.com/images/1911/1943%20errs%2061%20rr/remington_rand_errs.htm......This ERRS gun is very clean, one thing pretty common when they were given to Rem Rand employees is that they would engrave their initials on the gun, usually above the serial number (I've seen 3 like that and have pics of a couple), but this one has it engraved on the front left of slide....the initials in cursive "LA". You hardly notice they there-see pics. Has Mint High Standard barrel, Early Keyes Fiber Co. grips without screw reinforcement ring, Comes with Mint General Shaver mag with "G" on toe...This gun is in the Extremely Rare category, They do not come around very often...Don't miss your chance here, I know this will be going to a Hardcore Collector and whom ever you might be....I tip my hat to you! I don't really want to sell it...
